<HEADLINE>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="4"> FT 09 DEC 94 / EU border checks end in March</s>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="5"> By REUTER</s>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="6"> PARIS</s>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="7"> The Schengen accord to end border controls between nine European Union states will finally come into effect on March 26 next year, Mr Yves-Thibault de Silguy, one of France's new EU commissioners, told Le Figaro newspaper in an interview.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="8"> 'Schengen's all sorted out.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="9"> On December 22, we will announce that the accords come into effect on March 26,' said Mr de Silguy, who takes over as economic and monetary affairs commissioner at the end of next month.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="10"> 'On that date Schengen starts being applied and the signatory countries must take measures to get rid of border controls before the summer,' he said.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="11"> Officials from the nine are due to meet in Heidelberg, Germany, on December 22 to set an official implementation date, which has been put back since January 1993.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="12"> Last month, Germany said the accords should come into effect by April at the latest.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="13"> Germany, France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg, Italy, Spain, Portugal and Greece have signed the accord.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="14"> Austria, which joins the EU next month, has observer status.</s>

<s docid="FT944-4056" num="15"> Britain, Ireland and Denmark have kept their distance as have the two other new members, Finland and Sweden.</s>
</TEXT>
